HE POLITICS OF PSYCHIATRY-BODIES, ILLNESSES, AND MENTAL HEALTH -- tThe Hygiene of Everyday Life and the Politics of Turn-of-the-Century Psychiatric Expertise in Hungary -- tWho Is Mentally Ill? Psychiatry and the Individual in Interwar Germany -- tRussian Psychiatry beyond Foucault: Violence, Humanism, and Psychiatric Power in the Russian Empire at the End of the Nineteenth and Early Twentieth Century -- tPatients and Observers: Specific Data Collection Methods in an Interwar Transylvanian Hospital -- tContemporary Criticism and Defenses of Psychiatry's Moral-Medical Kinds in Light of Foucault's Lectures on the Abnormal -- tV. CRITICAL PSYCHOLOGY AND THE EPISTEMOLOGY OF PSY-KNOWLEDGE -- tNeoliberal Governmentality, Austerity, and Psycho-Politics -- tPsycho-Politics and Illness Constructions in the Background of the Trauma-Concept of the DSM-5 -- tIs Integration Possible for Psychoanalysis? -- tParallels, Intersections, and Clashes: Journeys through the Fringes -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex of Names0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPsy-sciences (psychology, psychiatry, psychoanalysis, pedagogy, criminology, special education, etc.) have been connected to politics in different ways since the early twentieth century. Here in twenty-two essays scholars address a variety of these intersections from a historical perspective. The chapters include such diverse topics as the cultural history of psychoanalysis, the complicated relationship between psychoanalysis and the occult, and the struggles for dominance between the various schools of psychology. They show the ambivalent positions of the "psy" sciences in the dictatorships and authoritarian regimes of Nazi Germany, East European communism, Latin-American military dictatorships, and South African apartheid, revealing the crucial role of psychology in legitimating and "normalizing" these regimes. The authors also discuss the ideological and political aspects of mental health and illness in Hungary, Germany, post-WW1 Transylvania, and Russia. Other chapters describe the attempt by critical psychology to understand the production of academic, therapeutic, and everyday psychological knowledge in the context of the power relations of modern capitalist societies.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aPolitical psychologyzEurope, EasternvCongresses. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / History.2bisacsh  aHistory of science, Prostitution, Psychiatry, Psychoanalysis, Psychology, Public health.1 aAgora, Zsuzsanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-Haim, Shaul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkovits, Balázs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBokor, Zsuzsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorgos, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorgos, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBorossa, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCsabai, Márta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimitrijević, Aleksandar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErős, Ferenc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErős, Ferenc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFox, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedrich, Melinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrosh, Step